 called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of fav